created high con&s;table; and the dig$ity of earl mare$chal conferred upon Ralph N$v$l earl of We$tmoreland. In a few days after this promotion, he be&s;towed the I$$e of Man upon the former of the&s;e noblemen, with the privilege of ca$|r$i$g at the c$ronation the $word of Lanca&s;ter, which was the very indivi$$al w$$p$$ he w$$e w$$n he landed $t Raven&s;pur. Then his &s;econd &s;o$ $ho|mas of Lanca$t$r was inv$&s;ted with the office of high &s;teward; a plac$ o$ dig|$ity whic$ $word$ wa$ o$$iged t$ f$ll before the coronation, becau&s;e the high &s;t w|ard d$c$des the right o$ tho&s;e part$cul$r noblemen who per$$rm partic$l$$ $word$ at that ceremony; and a$ Thomas was but ten year$ of age at this per$$d, Thomas Piercy earl of Worce&s;ter was app$inted his lie$tenant. Henry &s;$ems<NOTE PLACE="marg">A$t$ Pub.</NOTE> to have made his religion &s;ub&s;ervient to his intere&s;t. We have &s;een how he $a&s;|cinated the eyes of the people with public $cts of devotion in St. Paul's church, when he brought $is &s;overeign a pri&s;oner to London, as well as at his u&s;urpation in We&s;tmin&s;ter$Hall; and now to carry on t$e &s;ame &s;uper&s;titious mummery, in which he found his account, he re&s;olved to be a$ointed at his coronation, with a certain oil &s;aid to have been pre&s;ented by the Virgin Mary to Thomas Becket during his exile. The phial that contained this precious balm had fallen into the hands of a$ hermit, who gave it to Henry duke of Lanca&s;ter grand&s;on of Henry III. a&s;&s;uring him, that all the kings anointed with that oil would become the true champions of the church. The duke made a pre&s;ent of it to Edward the Black Prince, who intended to be anointed with it, had he lived to his co|ronation: but after his death the phial, which was of &s;tone &s;$rmounted by a golden eagle adorned with precious &s;tones, &s;tood for &s;ome time unheeded among his jewels until the latter part of his reig$, immediately before his la&s;t expedition to Ireland, when