&sect; <HI>LI.</HI> The duke of Bedford dies at Ro$en; and is &s;ucceeded as regent $y Richard duke of York. &sect; <HI>LII.</HI> Charles becomes ma&s;ter of Paris. &sect; <HI>LIII.</HI> The duke of Burgundy undertakes the &s;iege of Calais. &sect; <HI>LIV.</HI> The Engli&s;h are wor$$ed at Popperden in Scotland. &sect; <HI>LV.</HI> Death of Catherine, widow of Henry <HI>V.</HI> &sect; <HI>LVI.</HI> Proceedings in parliament. &sect; <HI>LVII.</HI> Talbot &s;urprizes Pont$i&s;e, and rai&s;es the &s;iege of Crotoy. &sect; <HI>LVIII.</HI> Charles takes Montereau, and enters Paris in triu$ph. &sect; <HI>LIX.</HI> The cardinal's intere&s;t triumphs over that of Glouce&s;ter. &sect; <HI>LX.</HI> James king of Scotland is a&s;&s;a&s;&s;$ated. &sect; <HI>LXI.</HI> The con&s;table takes Meaux; and Talbot reduces Har$$e$r.</P>
